summary:
A three-judge panel of Rwanda-backed M23 rebels overran Congolese troops and entered Goma on Friday amid gunfire and shelling. The capture traps more than one million displaced residents in the eastern Congo aid hub. United Nations evacuation plans are advancing. This affects civilians in Africa's conflict with the highest death toll since 1998.

In Gaza, Israel permitted over one million displaced Palestinians to cross back into northern Gaza after resolving a hostage release deadlock that bisected the enclave. Further population movements depend on cease-fire talks. Separately, NATO activated its first coordinated response after a deep-sea cable was severed in the Baltic Sea in a suspected sabotage campaign targeting infrastructure. Baltic nations and NATO allies are securing networks while investigations identify culprits.

The U.S. Treasury sanctioned a major Chinese oil refinery and about 40 shipping firms and tankers for transporting Iranian petroleum, enforcing restrictions on Iran's oil exports. Further actions are possible. Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth testified for six hours before lawmakers on Iran war strategy, facing Democratic questions in the first oversight hearing since the conflict began; additional hearings are scheduled. A U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit panel ruled President Trump's executive order suspending border asylum illegal, halting enforcement pending a likely Supreme Court appeal. The Fourth Circuit in Richmond lifted a block on Trump's orders against federal DEI programs, resuming enforcement. The Justice Department authorized firing squads alongside pentobarbital injections for federal executions to accelerate cases. Federal prosecutors indicted Sinaloa Governor Rubén Rocha Moya for a conspiracy protecting cartel operations; extradition may follow. A SpaceX Falcon 9 launched the Crew-10 mission from Kennedy Space Center at 7:03 p.m. Friday with NASA astronauts Anne McClain and Nichole Ayers, Japan's Takuya Onishi, and Russia's Kirill Peskov to retrieve Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams, stuck on the ISS for nine months; docking is set for Saturday night."}
